===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|magik|lang=enm}} from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|magique|lang=fro}}, reborrowed from {{etyl|la}} {{term|magice|lang=la}}, borrowed from {{etyl|grc}} {{term|sc=polytonic|μαγική|lang=grc||magical}} ({{term|sc=polytonic|τέχνη|lang=grc||art}}), derived from {{term|sc=polytonic|μάγος|tr=mage|lang=grc}} from {{term|magos magus}}, sorcerer, of Iranian origin; akin to Old Persian {{term|𐎶𐎦𐎢𐏁|sc=Xpeo|tr=maguš||sorcerer}}. Displaced native [[Middle English]] ''[[dweomercraft#Middle English|dweomercraft]]'' "magic, magic arts" (from [[Old English]] ''[[dwimor#Old English|dwimor]]'' "phantom, illusion" + ''[[cræft#Old English|cræft]]'' "art"), [[Old English]] ''[[galdorcræft#Old English|galdorcræft]]'' "magic, enchantment", [[Old English]] ''[[drycræft#Old English|drȳcræft]]'' "magic, sorcery".

